    {
      "id": "1e307e76d89b19d2196a5b51f38c97d49da55d1b",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 229,
        "name": "Bruno Faccini",
        "email": "bfaccini@nvidia.com",
        "username": "bfaccini"
      },
      "date": "2015-11-16 10:16:38.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nLiang, I have still a concern about the \"stealing case\" in lnet_ptl_match_delay(), that it releases both lnet_[res,ptl]_lock() between each LNET_CPT_NUMBER loop, this leaves a potential window where an other thread can run lnet_ptl_attach_md() causing lnet_msg to be list_del_init(), then don't you think that the next \"if (!list_empty(&msg->msg_list))\" tests will be fooled ?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "c005546fe62193f0a8c83651f33c1a1d651f0e48",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 176,
        "name": "Liang Zhen",
        "email": "liang.zhen@intel.com",
        "username": "liangzhen",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2015-11-18 07:29:21.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nI think the next \"\"if (!list_empty(&msg->msg_list))\" should be checked with hold of lock right? so the question can be simplified to:\n* one thread take a lock and delete the message from a list then release the lock\n* the other thread takes the lock and check if the message is still on the list\n\nI think it is safe right?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "83e362b5434a3d99d20380d953346342f993b2f1",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 229,
        "name": "Bruno Faccini",
        "email": "bfaccini@nvidia.com",
        "username": "bfaccini"
      },
      "date": "2015-11-18 18:48:01.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1\n\nThis time (for the \"stealing\" case), I did not mean it is unsafe on a link-list coherency point of view, but seems to me that the  fact lnet_ptl_attach_md() can unlink a msg from ptl_msg_stealing list, may break the algorithm in lnet_ptl_match_md()/lnet_ptl_match_delay() ... But you know it much better than me ;-)",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
